1. High‑Level Components (Boxes)
Kahana implementation includes:

Clients

Oasis client (Firefox-based browser). OTA updates delivered via canary/stable rings; update service (Supabase function) serves update.xml and MAR files. Users receive updates in-app (Settings → Oasis Updates). Critical: update URL must not point to Mozilla—would overwrite Oasis branding.

Edge / API Layer

Web/API gateway / load balancer (receives HTTPS requests).

Application Services (Oasis Backend)

Auth & Session service (handles login, tokens, SSO).

Workspace / Hubs service (workspaces, structures, metadata).

User & Org service (accounts, org membership, roles).

AI/Assistant service (calls out to AI providers, if applicable).

Notification / Email service (optional).

Data Stores

Primary relational database (user accounts, workspace metadata, configs).

Object storage (any stored files or attachments, if applicable).

Caches (Redis, etc. – optional).

Support Services

OTA Update Service: Supabase function (oasis-update/index.ts) serving canary/stable rings; ring pointers control which version users receive. Rollback = repoint pointer.

Logging / Monitoring system (Supabase logs, Mixpanel).

Secrets management (AWS Secrets Manager).

CI/CD pipeline (GitHub Actions: oasis-canary.yml, oasis-stable-promote.yml; MAR build/sign via scripts/update-signing).

Third‑Party Services

Identity/SSO provider.

Payment/billing provider.

AI provider(s) (if used).

Email/notifications provider (if used).

